@@WSaffron Walk@@N~
Warm ochre plaster coats the buildings along this walk, and the street takes its name from the saffron traders who once dominated the block before the spice markets consolidated further south. The aroma of lamp oil and dried herbs still lingers in the sheltered doorways, and a saint's niche carved into the eastern wall holds a cluster of tallow candles kept lit by neighbourhood custom. Foot traffic thins here compared to the busier market stretches, giving the walk a contemplative pace that suits the apothecaries and bookbinders who have taken over the old spice stalls.
