A formal iron-and-stone gatehouse marks the civic threshold between @@WMidgaard@@N's upper streets and the @@pPublic Dungeon@@N below. Registry scribes occupy a narrow booth beside the descent stair, recording names and charges in heavy ledger books chained to their desks, while a mercy-petition box bolted to the wall collects sealed pleas from relatives of the confined. The yard itself is paved with close-set granite blocks and kept scrupulously clean by municipal order, though the air carries a damp chill rising from the passages below. Guard details rotate here on four-hour shifts, their presence reinforced by posted civic ordinances detailing the rights of the accused. A worn stone bench along the eastern wall accommodates petitioners who wait for intake hearings, and faded @@pward marks@@N on the gatehouse lintel record the sealing of three unauthorized tunnel breaches from the Fortification Era.
