Oxidized bronze columns line both sides of this institutional stretch, their verdigris patina lending the colonnade a blue-green cast that shifts with the light. The columns were erected during the Standardization Century to mark the boundary of the central administrative district, and their bases still bear the Lantern Reform seal in raised relief. Government clerks and petition-bearers dominate the foot traffic here, moving between the offices that occupy the ground floors behind the colonnade.
