The limestone facades on the third tier of Sunward Way are streaked with rain channels where decades of runoff have carved shallow grooves into the stone. Despite the weathering, the street retains its characteristic warmth, and a produce cart stationed at the midpoint sells winter apples and dried figs to the clerks and temple staff who use this route as a shortcut between districts. The paving here includes several broad flagstones inscribed with directional arrows from the Lantern Reform wayfinding system.
