A broad stone arch marks the western caravan entrance to @@WMidgaard@@N, wide enough for two laden wagons to pass abreast and flanked by guard towers whose arrow loops command the approach road. Customs officers maintain an inspection station inside the arch, where incoming cargo is weighed, assessed, and stamped before proceeding to the market districts. The pavement beneath the arch is grooved by decades of iron-rimmed wheels, and the walls bear carved distance markers indicating the leagues to major trading destinations. Posted travel bulletins warn of bandit activity and road conditions on the western routes, their information updated weekly by the Road Warden Liaison. The gate's keystone bears the city seal flanked by carved sheaves of grain, symbolizing the trade that sustains @@WMidgaard@@N's prosperity.
