The lower Golden Mews shares the narrow proportions of its upper counterpart but lacks the professional tile work — here the walls are plain mortared stone with occasional patches of whitewash applied by individual tenants rather than any civic program. A row of wooden pegs driven into the wall at shoulder height serves as an informal message system, with folded notes and delivery tags pinned beneath numbered brass tacks. The passage sees steady foot traffic from residents and delivery runners who use it as a shortcut between the market streets and the southern residential quarter.
