The dark volcanic stone continues along this lower section of the crescent, its heat-retaining properties even more pronounced in the confined space between the taller buildings here. The curved wall creates a natural wind shelter, and on cold evenings this stretch becomes an informal gathering spot where residents bring stools and small braziers to enjoy the radiant warmth while sharing stories and complaints about the ward administration. A mosaic of small obsidian chips set into the pavement near the curve's apex depicts the outline of a mountain, possibly a reference to the volcanic source of the building stone.
